{"title_page": "L\u00e9on Mokuna", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Congolese footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|embed          = \n|name           = L\u00e9on Mokuna\n|image          = \n|image_size     = \n|alt            = \n|caption        = \n|fullname       = L\u00e9on Motombo Mokuna\n|birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1928|11|01}}\n|birth_place    = [[Belgian Congo]]<br/><small>(modern-day [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DR Congo]])</small>\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|01|28|1928|11|01}}\n|death_place    = [[Ghent]], Belgium\n|height         = 1.75 m<ref name=\"wf\">{{Worldfootball.net|trouet-mokuna}}</ref>\n|position       = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=\"wf\"/>\n|youthyears1    = \n|youthclubs1    = \n|years1         = 1954\n|clubs1         = [[AS Vita Club]]\n|caps1          = \n|goals1         = \n|years2         = 1954\u20131957\n|clubs2         = [[Sporting CP|Sporting Lisbon]]\n|caps2          = 13\n|goals2         = 19\n|years3         = 1957\n|clubs3         = [[AS Vita Club]]\n|caps3          = \n|goals3         = \n|years4         = 1957\u20131961\n|clubs4         = [[AA Gent|KAA Gent]]\n|caps4          = \n|goals4         = \n|years5         = 1961\u20131966\n|clubs5         = [[SV Waregem]]\n|caps5          = \n|goals5         = \n|totalcaps      = \n|totalgoals     = \n|nationalyears1 = 1959\n|nationalteam1  = [[Belgium national football B team|Belgium B]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 2\n|nationalgoals1 = 1\n|medaltemplates = \n|manageryears1  = 1968\u20131970\n|managerclubs1  = [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]]\n}}\n\n'''L\u00e9on Motombo Mokuna''' (1 November 1928 \u2013 28 January 2020),<ref>[http://www.leballonrond.fr/jogador.php?id=108248 Le ballon ronde]</ref> nicknamed '''''Le Trouet''''' or '''''Trouet''''', was a Belgian-[[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congolese]] professional [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[Sporting CP|Sporting Lisbon]], [[AA Gent|KAA Gent]] and [[SV Waregem]] between 1954 and 1966. He was among the first Africans to play professionally in Belgium, and may have been the first Congolese player in a European side. His role has been described as \"pioneering\" by [[BBC Sport]].<ref name=BBCObit>{{cite news |last1=Gleeson |first1=Mark |title=Pioneering DR Congo forward Leon Mokuna dies aged 90 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51296004 |accessdate=31 January 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Voetbalclubs eren L\u00e9on Mokuna |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/3831qo3o |accessdate=31 January 2020 |agency=GHL/ABG |publisher=Het Nieuwsblad |date=5 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nL\u00e9on Mokuna was born in the [[Belgian Congo]] in 1928 and grew up in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]] (now Kinshasa) where he became a proteg\u00e9 of the football-promoting [[CICM Missionaries|Scheutist]] missionary [[Rapha\u00ebl de la Kethulle de Ryhove]], known as \"Tata Rapha\u00ebl\". Playing football in L\u00e9opoldville, Mokuna gained the French nickname ''Le Trouet'' or ''Trouet'' (\"little hole\", phonetically derived from ''trou\u00e9!'' or \"holed!\") for reputedly having scoring a [[Goal (sports)|goal]] with such force that it snapped the net. He retained it throughout his playing career.<ref name=BBCObit/>\n\n==Football career==\nMokuna was originally talent-spotted by [[Sporting CP|Sporting Lisbon]] which visited L\u00e9opoldville in 1954 during a tour of neighbouring [[Portuguese Angola]]. He moved to [[Estado Novo (Portugal)|Portugal]] to play for Sporting from January 1955 and finished the season with 19 goals in 11 games. However, he remained with the team for only two seasons after being \"ostracised\" before returning to the Congo to play for [[AS Vita Club]] at L\u00e9opoldville.<ref name=BBCObit/> \n\nIn 1957, Mokuna left the Congo for Belgium to play for [[KAA Gent]] (\"La Gantoise\") where he was twice the team's top goalscorer (1959 and 1960) and became \"a club icon\".<ref name=BBCObit/> At the time, it was widely assumed that Mokuna was the first African to play for a Belgian team and the first Congolese player in a European club. He certainly pre-empted the so-called ''Belgicains'' who arrived from the Congo to play at Belgian clubs after 1959. However, a mixed-race player [[Louis Cousin (boxer)|Louis Cousin]] (1912\u201389) had played for [[R. Daring Club Molenbeek|Daring Brussels]] during the 1930s and is now thought to hold the title.<ref name=Radio2/>\n\nMokuna played twice for the [[Belgium national football B team]] in 1959. He became the first black player to represent the country, though he blamed racial prejudice for not being selected for the [[Belgium national football team|main national side]] during the same period.<ref name=BBCObit/> He left KAA Gent in 1961, later playing for [[KSV Waregem]] (1961\u201366) and [[KV Kortrijk]] where he immediately suffered a double fracture to his leg that ended his playing career.<ref name=BBCObit/> He gained Belgian nationality in 1959.\n\nAfter [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Congolese independence]] in 1960, Mokuna coached the [[DR Congo national football team|national football team]] ahead of the [[1965 Africa Cup of Nations]] during the country's first appearance in [[Africa Cup of Nations|the tournament]]. The team lost to [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] and [[Cote d'Ivoire national football team|Cote d'Ivoire]] and was eliminated.<ref name=BBCObit/>\n\n==Later life==\nMokuna returned to the Congo (later [[Zaire]]) after the end of his Belgian football career and worked in business.<ref name=\"BBCObit\" /> He managed the Congolese national team from 1968 to 1970. However, his property was confiscated by the regime of [[Mobutu Sese Seko]] and he returned to Belgium in 1989. \n\nHe remained in [[Ghent]] until his death at age 91 on 28 January 2020.<ref name=\"Radio2\">{{cite news |title=L\u00e9on Mokuna (91), een van eerste zwarte voetballers in Belgi\u00eb, overleden |url=https://radio2.be/oost-vlaanderen/leon-mokuna-91-een-van-eerste-zwarte-voetballers-in-belgie-overleden |accessdate=31 January 2020 |publisher=Radio 2 |date=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DR Congo national football team managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mokuna}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kinshasa]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Belgian Congo people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgian footballers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:AS Vita Club players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP footballers]]\n[[Category:K.A.A. Gent players]]\n[[Category:K.S.V. Waregem players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo football managers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo emigrants to Belgium]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo exiles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Congolese footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|embed          = \n|name           = L\u00e9on Mokuna\n|image          = \n|image_size     = \n|alt            = \n|caption        = \n|fullname       = L\u00e9on Motombo Mokuna\n|birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1928|11|01}}\n|birth_place    = [[Belgian Congo]]<br/><small>(modern-day [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DR Congo]])</small>\n|death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|01|28|1928|11|01}}\n|death_place    = [[Ghent]], Belgium\n|height         = 1.75 m<ref name=\"wf\">{{Worldfootball.net|trouet-mokuna}}</ref>\n|position       = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]<ref name=\"wf\"/>\n|youthyears1    = \n|youthclubs1    = \n|years1         = 1954\n|clubs1         = [[AS Vita Club]]\n|caps1          = \n|goals1         = \n|years2         = 1954\u20131957\n|clubs2         = [[Sporting CP|Sporting Lisbon]]\n|caps2          = 13\n|goals2         = 19\n|years3         = 1957\n|clubs3         = [[AS Vita Club]]\n|caps3          = \n|goals3         = \n|years4         = 1957\u20131961\n|clubs4         = [[AA Gent|KAA Gent]]\n|caps4          = \n|goals4         = \n|years5         = 1961\u20131966\n|clubs5         = [[SV Waregem]]\n|caps5          = \n|goals5         = \n|totalcaps      = \n|totalgoals     = \n|nationalyears1 = 1959\n|nationalteam1  = [[Belgium national football B team|Belgium B]]\n|nationalcaps1  = 2\n|nationalgoals1 = 1\n|medaltemplates = \n|manageryears1  = 1968\u20131970\n|managerclubs1  = [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]]\n}}\n\n'''L\u00e9on Motombo Mokuna''' (1 November 1928 \u2013 28 January 2020),<ref>[http://www.leballonrond.fr/jogador.php?id=108248 Le ballon ronde]</ref> nicknamed '''''Le Trouet''''' or '''''Trouet''''', was a Belgian-[[Democratic Republic of the Congo|Congolese]] professional [[association football|footballer]] who played for [[Sporting CP|Sporting Lisbon]], [[AA Gent|KAA Gent]] and [[SV Waregem]] between 1954 and 1966. He was among the first Africans to play professionally in Belgium, and may have been the first Congolese player in a European side. His role has been described as \"pioneering\" by [[BBC Sport]].<ref name=BBCObit>{{cite news |last1=Gleeson |first1=Mark |title=Pioneering DR Congo forward Leon Mokuna dies aged 90 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51296004 |accessdate=31 January 2020 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Voetbalclubs eren L\u00e9on Mokuna |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/3831qo3o |accessdate=31 January 2020 |agency=GHL/ABG |publisher=Het Nieuwsblad |date=5 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nL\u00e9on Mokuna was born in the [[Belgian Congo]] in 1928 and grew up in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]] (now Kinshasa) where he became a proteg\u00e9 of the football-promoting [[CICM Missionaries|Scheutist]] missionary [[Rapha\u00ebl de la Kethulle de Ryhove]], known as \"Tata Rapha\u00ebl\". Playing football in L\u00e9opoldville, Mokuna gained the French nickname ''Le Trouet'' or ''Trouet'' (\"little hole\", phonetically derived from ''trou\u00e9!'' or \"holed!\") for reputedly having scoring a [[Goal (sports)|goal]] with such force that it snapped the net. He retained it throughout his playing career.<ref name=BBCObit/>\n\n==Football career==\nMokuna was originally talent-spotted by [[Sporting CP|Sporting Lisbon]] which visited L\u00e9opoldville in 1954 during a tour of neighbouring [[Portuguese Angola]]. He moved to [[Estado Novo (Portugal)|Portugal]] to play for Sporting from January 1955 and finished the season with 19 goals in 11 games. However, he remained with the team for only two seasons after being \"ostracised\" before returning to the Congo to play for [[AS Vita Club]] at L\u00e9opoldville.<ref name=BBCObit/> \n\nIn 1957, Mokuna left the Congo for Belgium to play for [[KAA Gent]] (\"La Gantoise\") where he was twice the team's top goalscorer (1959 and 1960) and became \"a club icon\".<ref name=BBCObit/> At the time, it was widely assumed that Mokuna was the first African to play for a Belgian team and the first Congolese player in a European club. He certainly preempted the Congolese ''Belgicains'' who arrived to play at Belgian clubs after 1959. However, a mixed-race player [[Louis Cousin (boxer)|Louis Cousin]] (1912\u201389) had played for [[R. Daring Club Molenbeek|Daring Brussels]] during the 1930s and is now thought to hold the title.<ref name=Radio2/>\n\nMokuna played twice for the [[Belgium national football B team]] in 1959. He became the first black player to represent the country, though he blamed racial prejudice for not being selected for the [[Belgium national football team|main national side]] during the same period.<ref name=BBCObit/> He left KAA Gent in 1961, later playing for [[KSV Waregem]] (1961\u201366) and [[KV Kortrijk]] where he immediately suffered a double fracture to his leg that ended his playing career.<ref name=BBCObit/> He gained Belgian nationality in 1959.\n\nAfter [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Congolese independence]] in 1960, Mokuna coached the [[DR Congo national football team|national football team]] ahead of the [[1965 Africa Cup of Nations]] during the country's first appearance in [[Africa Cup of Nations|the tournament]]. The team lost to [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] and [[Cote d'Ivoire national football team|Cote d'Ivoire]] and was eliminated.<ref name=BBCObit/>\n\n==Later life==\nMokuna returned to the Congo (later [[Zaire]]) after the end of his Belgian football career and worked in business.<ref name=\"BBCObit\" /> He managed the Congolese national team from 1968 to 1970. However, his property was confiscated by the regime of [[Mobutu Sese Seko]] and he returned to Belgium in 1989. \n\nHe remained in [[Ghent]] until his death at age 91 on 28 January 2020.<ref name=\"Radio2\">{{cite news |title=L\u00e9on Mokuna (91), een van eerste zwarte voetballers in Belgi\u00eb, overleden |url=https://radio2.be/oost-vlaanderen/leon-mokuna-91-een-van-eerste-zwarte-voetballers-in-belgie-overleden |accessdate=31 January 2020 |publisher=Radio 2 |date=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DR Congo national football team managers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mokuna}}\n[[Category:1928 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kinshasa]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Belgian Congo people]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo footballers]]\n[[Category:Belgian footballers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:AS Vita Club players]]\n[[Category:Sporting CP footballers]]\n[[Category:K.A.A. Gent players]]\n[[Category:K.S.V. Waregem players]]\n[[Category:Belgian First Division A players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo football managers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo emigrants to Belgium]]\n[[Category:Democratic Republic of the Congo exiles]]\n", "name_user": "Brigade Piron", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFootball career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%C3%A9on_Mokuna"}
{"title_page": "Jon Burnside", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{update|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Jon Burnside\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| office1      = [[Toronto City Council]]lor for [[Don Valley West|Ward 26 (Don Valley West)]]\n| term_start1  = December 1, 2014\n| term_end1    = December 1, 2018\n| predecessor1 = [[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]]\n| successor1   = [[Jaye Robinson]] <small>(Ward 15)</small>\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = \n| residence    = \n| religion     = \n| nationality  = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| spouse       = \n| occupation   = \n}}\n\n'''Jon Burnside''' ({{Audio-nohelp|Jonburnside-mg.ogg|listen}}) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician.  He was the  [[Toronto City Council]] councillor for [[Don Valley West|Ward 26 (Don Valley West)]] for the years 2014\u20132018.<ref name=wins>[https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/toronto2014election/2014/10/27/jon_burnside_wins_ward_26_don_valley_west.html \"Jon Burnside wins Ward 26, Don Valley West\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', October 27, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nPrior to his election as a City councillor, Burnside worked as a police officer,<ref name=wins/> and later launched his own meal delivery company.<ref name=wins/>\n\n==Career as a councillor==\n\nBurnside first ran as a City councillor for Ward 26 in the [[2010 Toronto municipal election|2010 election]], losing narrowly to incumbent councillor [[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]].<ref name=wins/> He defeated Parker in the [[2014 Toronto municipal election|2014 election]].<ref name=wins/>\n\nIn October 2015 Burnside voiced concern when he learned that [[MetroLinx]] was partnering with [[Countrywide Homes]], over plans for [[Bayview LRT station]] on the [[Eglinton Crosstown LRT]], at [[Bayview Avenue, Toronto|Bayview]] and [[Eglinton Avenue, Toronto|Eglinton]] avenues.<ref name=PostCity2015-10-13/><ref name=Bayview2013-11-07/>\nCountrywide owns the property that currently houses a [[McDonald's]] restaurant on the corner where the main entrance to the station will be built.  Burnside learned that, rather than purchase the property outright, MetroLinx acquired the property, and several adjacent properties, in a deal that will allow Countrywide to build a new building above the station.  Burnside was concerned that the developers would plan to build taller than the nine storeys the site is currently zoned for.\n:{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n:''\"Metrolinx will profit per buildable square foot. So the bigger the development, the more money they get. [It\u2019s] the taxpayer\u2019s dollar [that] is building the Eglinton Crosstown, so why should all the profit go to the private sector?\"<ref name=PostCity2015-10-13/>\n|}\n\nBurnside ran unsuccessfully for re-election as councillor in the [[2018 Toronto municipal election|2018 election]] in the newly constituted Ward 15 Don Valley West,  which has the same boundaries as [[Don Valley West (provincial electoral district)|Don Valley West]] against fellow incumbent councillor [[Jaye Robinson]] the councillor for former ward 25.\n\n===2014===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''[[2014 Toronto municipal election|2014 Toronto election]], Ward 23<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 General Election Results for City Ward 26 - Don Valley West|url=http://election.toronto.ca/epr2014/eprDetail.do?C;022,111,309,203,403,#1426689673010}}</ref>\n''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n| '''Jon Burnside'''||9,415||42.73%\n|-\n| [[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]] ||6,167||27.99%\n|-\n| Ishrath Velshi||3,055||13.86%\n|-\n| David Sparrow||1,786||8.11%\n|-\n| Wasim Vania||1,033||4.69%\n|-\n| Dimitre Popov||578||2.62%\n|-\n! Total|| 22,034 ||100.00%\n|}\n\n===2010===\n{| cellpadding=\"8\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[2010 Toronto municipal election|2010 Toronto election]], Ward 26'''<ref>[http://election.toronto.ca/epr/textlist.html City of Toronto elections page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101026084116/http://election.toronto.ca/epr/textlist.html |date=2010-10-26 }}</ref>\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#ddf; width:150px;\"| Candidate\n! style=\"background:#ddf;\"| Votes\n! style=\"background:#ddf;\"| %\n|-\n|[[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]] ||align=right| 6,203 ||align=right| 31.3\n|-\n|'''Jon Burnside''' ||align=right| 5,788 ||align=right| 29.2\n|-\n|Mohamed Dhanani ||align=right| 5,627 ||align=right| 28.4\n|-\n|Yunus Pandor ||align=right| 1,452 ||align=right| 7.3\n|-\n|Tanvir Ahmed ||align=right| 377 ||align=right| 1.9\n|-\n|Shaukat Malik ||align=right| 216 ||align=right| 1.1\n|-\n|Nawab Salim Khan ||align=right| 169 ||align=right| 0.9\n|-\n!Total||align=right| 19,832 ||align=right| 100\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Bayview2013-11-07>\n{{cite news\n| url         = http://www.bayview-news.com/2013/11/mcdonalds-to-be-demolished-for-bayview-lrt.html/\n| title       = McDonalds to be demolished for Bayview LRT\n| publisher   = [[Bayview News]]\n| date        = 2013-11-07\n| accessdate  = 2015-10-21\n| quote       = The Bayview-Eglinton station will be built on the site of the McDonalds restaurant \n}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=PostCity2015-10-13>\n{{cite news\n| url         = http://postcity.com/Eat-Shop-Do/Do/October-2015/Eglinton-LRT-station-plus-a-condo/\n| title       = Eglinton LRT station plus a condo at Bayview and Eglinton?\n| author      = Samantha Peska\n| publisher   = [[Post City]]\n| date        = 2015-10-13\n| quote       = Instead of purchasing or expropriating the site, Metrolinx chose to negotiate a deal with the owner of the property, Countrywide Homes, that would allow them to build above the station.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Toronto City Councillors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burnside, Jon}}\n[[Category:Toronto city councillors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Toronto police officers]]\n\n\n{{Ontario-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{update|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Jon Burnside\n| image        = \n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| office1      = [[Toronto City Council]]lor for [[Don Valley West|Ward 26 (Don Valley West)]]\n| term_start1  = December 1, 2014\n| term_end1    = December 1, 2018\n| predecessor1 = [[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]]\n| successor1   = [[Jaye Robinson]] <small>(Ward 15)</small>\n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = \n| residence    = \n| religion     = \n| nationality  = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| spouse       = \n| occupation   = \n}}\n\n'''Jon Burnside''' ({{Audio-nohelp|Jonburnside-mg.ogg|listen}}) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician.  He was the  [[Toronto City Council]] councillor for [[Don Valley West|Ward 26 (Don Valley West)]] for the years 2014-2018.<ref name=wins>[https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/toronto2014election/2014/10/27/jon_burnside_wins_ward_26_don_valley_west.html \"Jon Burnside wins Ward 26, Don Valley West\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', October 27, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nPrior to his election as a City councillor, Burnside worked as a police officer,<ref name=wins/> and later launched his own meal delivery company.<ref name=wins/>\n\n==Career as a councillor==\n\nBurnside first ran as a City councillor for Ward 26 in the [[2010 Toronto municipal election|2010 election]], losing narrowly to incumbent councillor [[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]].<ref name=wins/> He defeated Parker in the [[2014 Toronto municipal election|2014 election]].<ref name=wins/>\n\nIn October 2015 Burnside voiced concern when he learned that [[MetroLinx]] was partnering with [[Countrywide Homes]], over plans for [[Bayview LRT station]] on the [[Eglinton Crosstown LRT]], at [[Bayview Avenue, Toronto|Bayview]] and [[Eglinton Avenue, Toronto|Eglinton]] avenues.<ref name=PostCity2015-10-13/><ref name=Bayview2013-11-07/>\nCountrywide owns the property that currently houses a [[McDonald's]] restaurant on the corner where the main entrance to the station will be built.  Burnside learned that, rather than purchase the property outright, MetroLinx acquired the property, and several adjacent properties, in a deal that will allow Countrywide to build a new building above the station.  Burnside was concerned that the developers would plan to build taller than the nine storeys the site is currently zoned for.\n:{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n:''\"Metrolinx will profit per buildable square foot. So the bigger the development, the more money they get. [It\u2019s] the taxpayer\u2019s dollar [that] is building the Eglinton Crosstown, so why should all the profit go to the private sector?\"<ref name=PostCity2015-10-13/>\n|}\n\nBurnside ran unsuccessfully for re-election as councillor in the [[2018 Toronto municipal election|2018 election]] in the newly constituted Ward 15 Don Valley West,  which has the same boundaries as [[Don Valley West (provincial electoral district)|Don Valley West]] against fellow incumbent councillor [[Jaye Robinson]] the councillor for former ward 25.\n\n===2014===\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"8\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|Colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\"|'''[[2014 Toronto municipal election|2014 Toronto election]], Ward 23<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 General Election Results for City Ward 26 - Don Valley West|url=http://election.toronto.ca/epr2014/eprDetail.do?C;022,111,309,203,403,#1426689673010}}</ref>\n''' \n|-\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\" width=\"150px\" | Candidate\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | Votes\n! bgcolor=\"#DDDDFF\"  | %\n|-\n| '''Jon Burnside'''||9,415||42.73%\n|-\n| [[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]] ||6,167||27.99%\n|-\n| Ishrath Velshi||3,055||13.86%\n|-\n| David Sparrow||1,786||8.11%\n|-\n| Wasim Vania||1,033||4.69%\n|-\n| Dimitre Popov||578||2.62%\n|-\n! Total|| 22,034 ||100.00%\n|}\n\n===2010===\n{| cellpadding=\"8\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''[[2010 Toronto municipal election|2010 Toronto election]], Ward 26'''<ref>[http://election.toronto.ca/epr/textlist.html City of Toronto elections page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101026084116/http://election.toronto.ca/epr/textlist.html |date=2010-10-26 }}</ref>\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#ddf; width:150px;\"| Candidate\n! style=\"background:#ddf;\"| Votes\n! style=\"background:#ddf;\"| %\n|-\n|[[John Parker (Canadian politician)|John Parker]] ||align=right| 6,203 ||align=right| 31.3\n|-\n|'''Jon Burnside''' ||align=right| 5,788 ||align=right| 29.2\n|-\n|Mohamed Dhanani ||align=right| 5,627 ||align=right| 28.4\n|-\n|Yunus Pandor ||align=right| 1,452 ||align=right| 7.3\n|-\n|Tanvir Ahmed ||align=right| 377 ||align=right| 1.9\n|-\n|Shaukat Malik ||align=right| 216 ||align=right| 1.1\n|-\n|Nawab Salim Khan ||align=right| 169 ||align=right| 0.9\n|-\n!Total||align=right| 19,832 ||align=right| 100\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Bayview2013-11-07>\n{{cite news\n| url         = http://www.bayview-news.com/2013/11/mcdonalds-to-be-demolished-for-bayview-lrt.html/\n| title       = McDonalds to be demolished for Bayview LRT\n| publisher   = [[Bayview News]]\n| date        = 2013-11-07\n| accessdate  = 2015-10-21\n| quote       = The Bayview-Eglinton station will be built on the site of the McDonalds restaurant \n}}\n</ref>\n<ref name=PostCity2015-10-13>\n{{cite news\n| url         = http://postcity.com/Eat-Shop-Do/Do/October-2015/Eglinton-LRT-station-plus-a-condo/\n| title       = Eglinton LRT station plus a condo at Bayview and Eglinton?\n| author      = Samantha Peska\n| publisher   = [[Post City